x4freetext: Orela
First, flux shape was
deterined by this reaction. Second, normalized using
saturated-resonance technique and 4.9-eV resonance in
the 197Au(n,gamma).
The data in the En > 20 keV region were also
corrected for isotopic impurities using the cross
sections for 134,136Ba, 135Ba and 138Ba. The latest
ENDF/B-VI evaluations, normalized to the relevant
data set in the region above 100 keV, were used to
extend the data above 225 keV and 200 keV,
respectively, to make this correction.
No details are given.
No reply to author proof sent to P. Koehler.
Consequently, Fig. 2-3 were  digitized on 5/6/2013.
Bib updates.

and Dict. Added doi, corrected errors and author last
names, digitized Fig. 2-3.
The Maxwell-Boltzman averaged cross sections were
calculated from the experimental neutron capture data.

x4freetext: Barium carbonate powder.
Sample thickness 0.003026 atoms/B.
Pulse-height weighting. Flight path 40.116 m.
Pair of C6D6 scintillators.
For En < 20 keV, the resonances were
sufficiently well resolved so that they could be
fitted using the multilevel R-matrix code SAMMY. The
effective capture cross sections have not been
corrected for finite-thickness samples effects. The
corrections are included by the code SAMMY.
Fig.2, page 1560.

x4freetext: Barium carbonate powder.
Sample thickness 0.01349 atoms/B.
6Li-loaded glass scintillator.
Flight path 79.827 m.
For En < 20 keV, the resonances were
sufficiently well resolved so that they could be
fitted using the multilevel R-matrix code SAMMY.
Because of our new transmission data, accurate
corrections for the sometimes substantial resonance
self-shielding (and smaller multiple-scattering)
corrections could be applied on a
resonance-by-resonance basis using SAMMY. In the
unresolved resonance region (En > 20 keV), the
relatively small average corrections for these effects
were calculated using the code SESH.
Fig.2, page 1560.
